<section xml:id="section-trig-graphs" >
<title>Sine Wave Properties</title>

<introduction>

<p>We began by looking at trigonometric functions in the context of triangles where the represent the ratio of side lengths that is always the same for a given ratio no matter the size or location of a triangle. Here we will consider trigonometric functions in context of their graphs which have direct application.</p>

</introduction>

<subsection xml:id="subsection-angles">
	<title>Beyond Triangles</title>

	<p>In triangles every angle had to be less than <m>180^\circ</m> because the sum of the angles of a triangle are only <m>180^\circ</m>. However, in many applications rather than measuring angles on objects we are measuring how far or how many times around something has moved. Use the the illustration in <xref ref="figure-angle-repeat" /> to see how angles are measured and how the trig functions act on larger angles. Find each of the following.
	<ul>
		<li>Angle of measure <m>210^\circ</m></li>
		<li>Angle of measure <m>-90^\circ</m> (note the illustration won't display a negative angle value, but you can move there)</li>
		<li>Angle of measure <m>405^\circ</m> (note the illustration won't display an angle value that large, but you can move there)</li>
		<li><m>\sin(45^\circ)</m> and <m>\sin(315^\circ)</m></li>
	</ul></p>

